# Vercel Speed Insights Implementation

## Summary
Successfully installed and configured Vercel Speed Insights for this Next.js project following the latest official documentation from https://vercel.com/docs/speed-insights/quickstart.

## Changes Made

### 1. Package Installation
- **Added dependency**: `@vercel/speed-insights` version ^2.0.0
- **Files modified**: 
  - `package.json` - Added dependency entry
  - `package-lock.json` - Updated lockfile with 367 new packages

### 2. Code Integration
- **Modified**: `app/layout.tsx`
- **Changes**:
  - Added import: `import { SpeedInsights } from "@vercel/speed-insights/next";`
  - Added component: `<SpeedInsights />` at the end of the `<body>` element

## Implementation Details

The implementation follows the official Next.js App Router pattern (v13.5+):
- Used the Next.js-specific import path: `@vercel/speed-insights/next`
- Placed the `<SpeedInsights />` component inside the root layout's `<body>` tag
- This ensures Speed Insights tracks all pages across the application

## Verification

✅ **Build**: Completed successfully with no errors
✅ **Linter**: Passed with no new warnings or errors
✅ **Type Checking**: TypeScript compilation successful
✅ **Static Generation**: All 11 routes generated successfully

## Framework Detection
- **Framework**: Next.js 16.2.6
- **Router**: App Router
- **Package Manager**: npm (using package-lock.json)
- **Language**: TypeScript

## Notes
- Speed Insights will automatically track Core Web Vitals (LCP, FID, CLS, etc.)
- No additional configuration is required for basic functionality
- Data will be visible in the Vercel dashboard once the project is deployed
- The component is non-blocking and won't affect page performance
